{
  "texts": [
    "As such, every dataset is composed of images and annotations tailored towards a specific endpoint, which can create nontrivial problems for combining datasets from different sources to solve a single task such as segmentation.",
    "As the BraTS challenge is an important benchmark for the performance of segmentation models, examining the winning architectures of the past challenges provides an overview of the evolution of medical image segmentation architectures.",
    "One fundamental segmentation model is the U-Net, which was first introduced by Ronneberger et al.",
    "in 2015 31 and has been the basis of the winning segmentation models in BraTS since then as well as becoming ubiquitous in other medical image segmentation tasks such as segmenting intracranial metastases 32 and many other biological structures 33.",
    "The U-Net is composed of two main structures: the contracting path gradually downsamples the image and extracts features at lower spatial resolution and a higher semantic level, and then the expanding path re-combines these features to create the segmentation mask by gradually upsampling the image again to the input resolution."
  ]
}